- [[JavaScript]] [[assessment]]
	- **Learn JavaScript with HTML**
	- JavaScript is a lightweight, interpreted programming language. It is designed for creating network-centric applications. It is complimentary to and integrated with Java. JavaScript is very easy to implement because it is integrated with HTML. It is open and cross-platform.
	- **Why learn JavaScript?**
	- JavaScript is a MUST for students and working professionals to become great Software Engineers.  This is especially true when they are working in the Web Development Domain.
	- **Key advantages of learning JavaScript:**
	- ·      JavaScript is the most popular programming language in the world and that makes it a programmer’s great choice. Once you've learned JavaScript, it helps you to develop great front-end as well as back-end software using different JavaScript based frameworks like jQuery, Node.JS etc.
	- ·      JavaScript is everywhere, it comes installed on every modern web browser, and so to learn JavaScript you really do not need any special environment setup. For example, Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Safari and every browser you know as of today, supports JavaScript.
	- ·      JavaScript helps you create beautiful and crazy fast websites. You can develop your website using a console like look and feel and give your users the best Graphical User Experience.
	- ·      Due to high demand, there are many job opportunities and high pay for those who know JavaScript.
	- ·      There are lots of frameworks and Libraries already developed which can be used directly in your software development to reduce your time to market.
	- There could be thousands of good reasons to learn JavaScript Programming. But one thing is for sure, to learn any programming language, not only JavaScript, you just need to code, and code and finally code until you become an expert.

	- Carefully follow the requirements below:
	- **Starting with the HTML wrapper code in the Code Editor...**
	- **You may or may not use a <form>. Note that there is no backend process or program to submit a form to. **
	- **If you use a form and submit, you must suppress the default action or the page will clear/load unpredictable results.**
	- **Ask the user to input their first name, last name, a UserID, and a birthdate in type date format.  The UserID must contain an uppercase, a lowercase, a number, and be 8 to 12 chars long.  **
	- **Create a JS function to verify formats of the UserID field.**
	- **You will either need to use a For loop to iterate through your data fields character by character with JS functions like char.toUpperCase() and parsInt(char), or use Regular Expressions, to validate the UserID format.**
	- **Use the following variables (with exact variable names) to hold the data:**
	- ***uid* is UserID.**
	- ***fname* is first name.**
	- ***lname* is last name.**
	- ***birthday* is birthday, using type 'date'.**
	- **You have to write a function called “dateDiff” that accepts one date parameter and returns the number of days between the birthday provided and the current date.**
	- **Create an “Accept” button to execute your functions and create the following output:**
	- **If the UserID does not pass your verification, then print “Invalid UserID” to the Display window.**
	- **If the fname, lname, or birthday fields are left empty then print “Invalid fname” etc…**
	- **Print “fname lname you have been breathing for ### days!” where ### is the number returned by your dateDiff() function.  Remember to convert milliseconds to days and only return the integer (whole) number of days.**
	- **If the number of days is less than (365*18) then print “You are probably not old enough to take this class!”**
	- **Use document.getElementById().innerHtml to display results and information messages on the Display window.**
	- **Create a "For loop” that loops 20 times and uses code similar to:**
	- **let str = "";
	  str = str.padStart(i,”x”); // i is the loop counter**
	- **to print 20 lines of Xs from 1 to 20 Xs.  The first line should have a single X and the 20th line should have 20 Xs.**
	- **Your Xs should be printed on the Display page as depicted in the example below.**

		- ```html
		  <!DOCTYPE html>
		  <html>
		  <body>
		  
		  
		  <div>
		      <! put your HTML code to input data here >
		      <form id="myForm">
		      <label for="fname">First Name:</label>
		      <input type="text" id="fname" required><br><br>
		      
		      <label for="lname">Last Name:</label>
		      <input type="text" id="lname" required><br><br>
		      
		      <label for="uid">UserID:</label>
		      <input type="text" id="uid" required><br><br>
		      
		      <label for="birthday">Birthdate:</label>
		      <input type="date" id="birthday" required><br><br>
		      
		      <button type="button" onclick="submitForm()">Accept</button>
		    </form>
		    
		    <div id="display"></div>
		  </div>
		  
		  <script>
		      // put your JavaScript code to read HTML inputs
		      // and validate inputs here using if statements
		      // and document.getElementById().innerHTML to display results
		      // write your JS functions here
		      // write your JS Loop For here to print the Xs
		      // use something like document.write(str.padStart(i,"x") + "<br>");
		      // Function to verify the format of the UserID field
		  function verifyUserID(uid) {
		    // Regular expression pattern for UserID format validation
		    var pattern = /^(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*[A-Z])(?=.*\d)[a-zA-Z\d]{8,12}$/;
		    
		    // Test the UserID against the pattern
		    return pattern.test(uid);
		  }
		  
		  // Function to calculate the difference in days between two dates
		  function dateDiff(date) {
		    var currentDate = new Date();
		    var birthDate = new Date(date);
		    
		    // Calculate the time difference in milliseconds
		    var timeDiff = Math.abs(currentDate.getTime() - birthDate.getTime());
		    
		    // Convert milliseconds to days
		    var daysDiff = Math.floor(timeDiff / (1000 * 3600 * 24));
		    
		    return daysDiff;
		  }
		  
		  // Function to submit the form and display the results
		  function submitForm() {
		    // Get the form inputs
		    var fname = document.getElementById('fname').value;
		    var lname = document.getElementById('lname').value;
		    var uid = document.getElementById('uid').value;
		    var birthday = document.getElementById('birthday').value;
		    
		    // Verify the UserID format
		    var isValidUserID = verifyUserID(uid);
		    
		    // Check if any field is empty
		    if (fname === '' || lname === '' || uid === '' || birthday === '') {
		      document.getElementById('display').innerHTML = 'Invalid fields: Please fill in all the required information.';
		    }
		    // Check if the UserID is invalid
		    else if (!isValidUserID) {
		      document.getElementById('display').innerHTML = 'Invalid UserID';
		    }
		    else {
		      // Calculate the number of days since birthdate
		      var daysSinceBirth = dateDiff(birthday);
		      
		      // Display the output
		      document.getElementById('display').innerHTML = fname + ' ' + lname + ' you have been breathing for ' + daysSinceBirth + ' days!';
		      
		      // Check if the person is old enough
		      if (daysSinceBirth < (365 * 18)) {
		        document.getElementById('display').innerHTML += '<br>You are probably not old enough to take this class!';
		      }
		    }
		  }
		  
		  // Print 20 lines of X
		  var str = '';
		  for (var i = 1; i <= 20; i++) {
		    str += 'X'.padStart(i, 'X') + '<br>';
		  }
		  document.getElementById('display').innerHTML += '<br>' + str;    
		  </script>
		  
		  </body>
		  </html>
		   
		  ```
		- Version 2:
		- ```html
		  <!DOCTYPE html>
		  <html>
		  <head>
		  <title>JavaScript Assessment Challenge Project</title>
		  </head>
		  <body>
		  <h1>JavaScript Assessment Challenge Project</h1>
		  <div id="display"></div>
		  <form>
		  <input type="text" name="fname" placeholder="First Name">
		  <input type="text" name="lname" placeholder="Last Name">
		  <input type="text" name="uid" placeholder="UserID">
		  <input type="date" name="birthday">
		  <input type="button" value="Accept" onclick="validate()">
		  </form>
		  <script>
		  function validate() {
		    let uid = document.getElementById("uid").value;
		    let fname = document.getElementById("fname").value;
		    let lname = document.getElementById("lname").value;
		    let birthday = document.getElementById("birthday").value;
		  
		    // Check if the UserID is valid
		    let is_valid_uid = false;
		    for (let i = 0; i < uid.length; i++) {
		      let c = uid.charAt(i);
		      if (c.isUppercase() || c.isLowercase() || c.isDigit()) {
		        is_valid_uid = true;
		        break;
		      }
		    }
		  
		    // Check if the other fields are valid
		    let is_valid_fname = fname.length > 0;
		    let is_valid_lname = lname.length > 0;
		    let is_valid_birthday = birthday != null;
		  
		    // Display the results
		    let str = "";
		    if (!is_valid_uid) {
		      str += "Invalid UserID";
		    }
		    if (!is_valid_fname) {
		      str += "Invalid fname";
		    }
		    if (!is_valid_lname) {
		      str += "Invalid lname";
		    }
		    if (!is_valid_birthday) {
		      str += "Invalid birthday";
		    }
		  
		    if (str == "") {
		      let days = dateDiff(birthday);
		      str += fname + " " + lname + " you have been breathing for " + days + " days!";
		      if (days < 365 * 18) {
		        str += " You are probably not old enough to take this class!";
		      }
		    }
		  
		    document.getElementById("display").innerHTML = str;
		  }
		  
		  function dateDiff(birthday) {
		    let today = new Date();
		    let birthdate = new Date(birthday);
		    let diff = today - birthdate;
		    return Math.round(diff / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24));
		  }
		  </script>
		  </body>
		  </html>
		  
		  ```

		- ```txt
		  The provided code is an HTML document with embedded JavaScript code. It creates a form where the user can input their first name, last name, UserID, and birthdate. Upon clicking the "Accept" button, the form data is validated, and the results are displayed on the page. Additionally, it includes a loop to print 20 lines of X characters.
		  
		  Let's go through the code and explain each part:
		  
		  1. HTML structure:
		     - The code is enclosed within the `<html>` and `<body>` tags, defining the HTML document's structure.
		     - Inside the `<body>` tag, there is a `<div>` element that contains the form and a display section.
		     - The form has input fields for first name, last name, UserID, and birthdate, along with a button to submit the form.
		     - The display section is a `<div>` element with the id "display" where the results will be shown.
		  
		  2. JavaScript functions:
		     - `verifyUserID(uid)`: This function uses a regular expression pattern to validate the format of the UserID. It checks if the UserID contains at least one lowercase letter, one uppercase letter, one digit, and is between 8 and 12 characters long.
		     - `dateDiff(date)`: This function calculates the number of days between the current date and the provided birthdate. It uses JavaScript's Date object to perform the calculations.
		     - `submitForm()`: This function is executed when the user clicks the "Accept" button. It retrieves the input values from the form fields, verifies the UserID format, checks for empty fields, calculates the number of days since birth, and displays the results accordingly.
		  
		  3. Form submission and result display:
		     - In the HTML code, the button's `onclick` attribute is set to the `submitForm()` function. So when the button is clicked, the `submitForm()` function is executed.
		     - Inside `submitForm()`, the form input values are retrieved using `getElementById()`.
		     - The UserID is then validated using the `verifyUserID()` function.
		     - If any field is empty, an error message is displayed in the "display" section.
		     - If the UserID is invalid, an "Invalid UserID" message is displayed.
		     - If all inputs are valid, the number of days since birth is calculated using the `dateDiff()` function, and the result is displayed in the "display" section.
		     - If the person is below 18 years old (based on the calculated days), an additional message is appended to the result.
		  
		  4. Loop to print X characters:
		     - After the form submission and result display code, there is a `for` loop that iterates from 1 to 20.
		     - Inside the loop, the `padStart()` method is used to generate a string of X characters with a length corresponding to the current iteration.
		     - The generated string is concatenated with the previous lines of X characters.
		     - Finally, the concatenated string is appended to the "display" section using `innerHTML`.
		  
		  By running the HTML file in a browser, you will see the form, and upon submitting it, the results will be displayed along with the 20 lines of X characters.
		  
		  Make sure to understand each aspect of the code, including how the form inputs are accessed, how functions are called, and how the loop iterates and generates the lines of X characters.
